    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_power_shear_matrix"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Copy and edit the proof from <xref ref="act_math_ind_matrix"></xref>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_power_unit_matrix"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Write <m>M_n=\left[ \begin{array}{cc} 2^{n-1} \amp 2^{n-1} \\ 2^{n-1} \amp 2^{n-1} \end{array} \right]</m>.
          Induct on <m>n</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          First, when <m>n=1</m> we have
          <m>J^1 = J = \left[ \begin{array}{cc} 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{array} \right]</m> and also <m>M_1=\left[ \begin{array}{cc} 2^0 \amp 2^0\\ 2^0 \amp 2^0 \end{array} \right]= \left[ \begin{array}{cc} 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{array} \right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Next, assume <m>J^{n-1} = M_{n-1} = \left[ \begin{array}{cc} 2^{n-2} \amp  2^{n-2} \\ 2^{n-2} \amp  2^{n-2} \end{array}  \right]</m> for some integer <m>n \ge 2</m>.
          Then
          <me>
            J^n = JJ^{n-1} =AM_{n-1} = \left[ \begin{array}{cc} 1 \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp  1 \end{array}  \right]\left[ \begin{array}{cc} 2^{n-2} \amp  2^{n-2}\\ 2^{n-2} \amp  2^{n-2} \end{array}  \right] = \ldots =M_n
          </me>
        </p>
      </proof>
      <p>
        Fill in the missing algebra using <m>2^{n-2}+2^{n-2} = 2 \cdot 2^{n-2} = 2^{n-1}</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_power_another_matrix"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Copy and edit the proof from the Answers to <xref ref="exer_prove_power_unit_matrix"></xref>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_power_dilationshear_matrix"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Copy and edit the proof from the Answers to <xref ref="exer_prove_power_unit_matrix"></xref>.
        Note that
        <me>
          2(n-1)2^{n-2}+1(2^{n-1})=(n-1)2\cdot 2^{n-2} + 2^{n-1}=(n-1)2^{n-1} + 2^{n-1}
        </me>.
        To finish the algebra, factor out <m>2^{n-1}</m> to get
        <me>
          ((n-1)+1)2^{n-1} =n2^{n-1}
        </me>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_power_complicated_matrix"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Copy and edit the proof from the Answers to <xref ref="exer_prove_power_unit_matrix"></xref>.
        Note that
        <me>
          1(3^{n-1})+2(3^{n-1}-2^{n-1})=3^{n-1}+2(3^{n-1}) -2(2^{n-1})
        </me>.
        To finish the algebra, factor out <m>3^{n-1}</m> to get
        <me>
          (1+2)3^{n-1}-2\cdot 2^{n-1} =3\cdot 3^{n-1}-2\cdot 2^{n-1}=3^n-2^n
        </me>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
